The paper presents a game-theoretic approach to resource allocation among multiple agents, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of a karma accounting mechanism, which could be related to Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-categories. The paper also presents results on social welfare, which could be related to Learning (cs.LG) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
